---
import DashboardLayout from '@/layouts/Dashboard.astro';
---

<DashboardLayout>
  <article class="max-w-3xl leading-relaxed">
    <h2 class="mb-4 text-xl">About VulnTrends</h2>

    <p class="mb-4 text-vt-text-secondary">
      VulnTrends is an open-source project that tracks trends in vulnerability
      patching across major software manufacturers. The dashboard visualises
      vulnerabilities discovered, fixed, the time between discovery and patch,
      and vulnerability backlogs — all over time, with the ability to filter
      by manufacturer and switch between monthly and yearly granularity.
    </p>

    <h3 class="mt-8 mb-3 text-lg text-vt-text-secondary">Methodology</h3>

    <p class="mb-4 text-vt-text-secondary">
      Data is drawn from publicly available security advisories and
      vulnerability databases. Each source is fetched, normalised to a common
      schema, and aggregated into time-series data for visualisation.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-4 text-vt-text-secondary">
      Where multiple sources report the same vulnerability (identified by CVE
      ID), vendor-specific advisory data is preferred over the NVD/CVE record,
      as vendor advisories typically provide richer patch-timing information.
    </p>

    <h3 class="mt-8 mb-3 text-lg text-vt-text-secondary">Data confidence</h3>

    <p class="mb-4 text-vt-text-secondary">
      The "Time between discovery and patch" chart can only be calculated for
      CVEs where both a discovery date <em>and</em> a patch date are known.
      Most vendor advisories only publish a patch date, not a separate
      discovery date — the chart only shows the subset of CVEs with full
      data. This can over-represent vendors that publish more detail (e.g.
      Mozilla and Project Zero, which report Reported/Fixed timestamps), and
      under-represent vendors that don't.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-4 text-vt-text-secondary">
      The "data confidence" badge on the patch lag chart shows what fraction
      of records have both dates, and the "Hide low-confidence manufacturers"
      toggle filters out vendors whose data is too sparse to be meaningful.
      Cross-vendor comparisons should always be interpreted with this
      asymmetry in mind — a 0-day median patch lag usually means
      "missing discovery data", not "instant patching".
    </p>

    <h3 class="mt-8 mb-3 text-lg text-vt-text-secondary">Data sources</h3>

    <ul class="mb-4 pl-6 space-y-2 text-vt-text-secondary list-disc">
      <li><strong class="text-vt-text-primary">Mozilla</strong> — Mozilla Foundation Security Advisories (MFSA)</li>
      <li><strong class="text-vt-text-primary">Google</strong> — Chrome Releases blog and Project Zero</li>
      <li><strong class="text-vt-text-primary">Microsoft</strong> — Security Response Center (MSRC) CVRF API</li>
      <li><strong class="text-vt-text-primary">Apple</strong> — Security advisories (with NVD fallback)</li>
      <li><strong class="text-vt-text-primary">Project Zero</strong> — Issue tracker with disclosure timelines</li>
      <li><strong class="text-vt-text-primary">NVD/CVE</strong> — National Vulnerability Database (cross-vendor)</li>
    </ul>

    <h3 class="mt-8 mb-3 text-lg text-vt-text-secondary">Limitations</h3>

    <ul class="mb-4 pl-6 space-y-2 text-vt-text-secondary list-disc">
      <li>
        Discovery dates are not consistently available across all sources.
        Where a discovery date is unavailable, the advisory publication date
        is used as a proxy, which yields a 0-day patch lag (likely
        misleading — see the data confidence section above).
      </li>
      <li>
        Patch dates are only available when the source explicitly reports them.
        NVD records do not include patch dates.
      </li>
      <li>
        Backlog figures represent vulnerabilities that have been discovered
        but not yet patched, based on the dates available. Actual backlogs
        may differ if patch information is incomplete.
      </li>
      <li>
        Apple advisory data is scraped from HTML pages and may be affected by
        structural changes. When scraping fails, Apple-related CVEs from NVD
        are used as a fallback.
      </li>
      <li>
        The "Vulnerabilities fixed" chart counts records with a patch date.
        This is a reasonable proxy for "fixed" but may include records where
        the patch was a no-op or the vendor advisory covered multiple CVEs.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h3 class="mt-8 mb-3 text-lg text-vt-text-secondary">Neutral framing</h3>

    <p class="mb-4 text-vt-text-secondary">
      This project presents data as-is, without editorial annotations or
      interpretive labels. Users are encouraged to draw their own conclusions
      from the visualised trends.
    </p>

    <h3 class="mt-8 mb-3 text-lg text-vt-text-secondary">Licence</h3>

    <p class="mb-4 text-vt-text-secondary">
      VulnTrends is open-source software released under the MIT licence.
      The aggregated data is derived from publicly available sources and is
      provided for informational purposes.
    </p>

    <h3 class="mt-8 mb-3 text-lg text-vt-text-secondary">Who is behind this?</h3>

    <p class="mb-4 text-vt-text-secondary">
      VulnTrends is the work of <a href="https://github.com/robpomeroy" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Rob Pomeroy</a>.
    </p>
  </article>
</DashboardLayout>
